values:
&nbsp;It looks like we are losing 12 full timers, including folks with 5 years of seniority. End result, already financially stressed social programs are being ground into pulp. Now the civil servants will be joining the growing population of unemployed begging on the street corners. What a mess!&nbsp;

Why don't people understand that cutting social programs DOES NOT encourage people to go back to work? It just dumps all those needy people onto the street, along with the people who are working hard to help&nbsp;them.&nbsp;

This country has a seriously messed value system.

Well, we're both sick. Go figure. We were both&nbsp;feeling kind of tired all weekend, even through W's chill birthday party. Then Sunday afternoon it hit and both of us went down. Today was spent slowly eating our way through a third pot of chicken soup (the other two were consumed during the preceding week) and watching Akira Kirosawa movies. Now we are watching The Incredibles and eating popsicles. Ah the joys of feeling crappy.&nbsp;

W has to go back to work tomorrow, but I am taking another day off. Poor guy. I wish he had better benefits...

No big plans for the next week...skipping a few meetings to catch up on work and then a low key weekend...game on Friday...chilling at home the rest of the time. Well, I might bake. I have had a hankering for challah lately.&nbsp;

My folks finally made a decision about Christmas. They are coming out here for once. Woot! Well, W is not that excited really, but I think it will be fun. He has to work most of the time anyway, so it will be wine tasting with Dad and shopping for new clothes with Mom for a week. Yay! Fun! Oh, and cookies. Lots and lots of cookies.

&nbsp;

Well, it is down to the wire. We have unpacked MOST of the boxes in the new place and I have less than a week at my current job. Tomorrow will be my last day at my desk.&nbsp;I am both sad and strangely elated. I will miss this place and, most importantly, these people. However, the changes that have ousted me from my comfortable spot have brought other changes that would make my continued employment here decidedly less appealing. Namely, one individual whom I am not on friendly terms with (understatement of the century) will be relocating here. I am not at all sad to miss an opportunity to sit side-by-side with her&nbsp;insanity. This move has, also, pushed&nbsp;me into making contact with people I might otherwise have considered above my access. In the past two weeks I have&nbsp;met with three deans and the president of the extended learning college. I am playing all my cards to get onto&nbsp;the main campuses and into the academic side of things.&nbsp;Had I not been staring unemployment in the face, I might not have taken those risks.&nbsp;I hope they prove worthwhile. In the mean time, I will take the new position&nbsp;I have been offered and be happy for the paycheck.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Monday and Tuesday of next week will be training (the only training I get) for the new job. After our vacation, I will be dumped into a classroom of 60 people (all welfare recipients) without any assistance...baptism by fire. So, the beginning of next week will be interesting, as it will be my only chance to glean the&nbsp;information I need on how to run this program.

Wednesday will be my&nbsp;goodbyes and then trying to get on the road before 3:30, so we can make it to Boise with enough time to sleep a full eight hours in preparation for the 15 hour day of driving to follow.&nbsp;

By midnight on Thursday, we should have arrived at my folks' place in Colorado, exhausted and ready to be pampered for a few days. My childhood friend is getting married on Friday night in a ceremony that will likely prove fodder for conversation for many upcoming years. Saturday will be time with the folks and introducing W to all the friends he missed on the last trip. Sunday we are going to Cirque du Soleil and dinner at a French Patisserie.&nbsp;

Monday the 25th we head to Santa Fe for a real vacation,&nbsp;sans family. Details and photos will follow.&nbsp;&nbsp;

So...

many changes...

most of them good.

No word from my schools. I have reached a level of insanity that is totally new for me. I have made close to 100 pieces of jewelry in the last week, all in an effort to keep from checking the mailbox more than once a day. I even took a day off work to try to force myself to calm down. I used it to make more jewelry, walk to the bead store for more supplies to make even MORE jewelry, do dishes, cook, and snuggle with my&nbsp;poor sick boyfriend.&nbsp;It has not worked. I think I might have to resort to alcoholism and arson to calm the nerves.&nbsp;

Damn damn late mail!!!

On the plus side, my creative urges have increased. In addition to the jewelry, I have written almost every day and I am trying new recipes for dinner every night. Last night it was Jamaican Pork Kebabs, which were "eh". Tonight it was "Down Home Chicken and Greens," which I highly recommend. Tomorrow will be lamb gyros with yogurt and roasted garlic. The lamb is marinating in a yogurt sauce as we speak and should be very tender come tomorrow evening. If it is good enough and I still have not heard from any schools, I might post the recipe.&nbsp;

Well, off to discuss D&amp;D and switch the laundry. Yippee!
